WEBVTT

00:04.700 --> 00:05.048
.

00:05.092 --> 00:07.485
- Previously
on "New Amsterdam."

00:07.529 --> 00:08.834
- Looking for someone
who lived here years ago.

00:08.878 --> 00:10.445
Horace Reynolds.

00:10.488 --> 00:13.013
- Nobody by that name has lived
here since I've been around.

00:13.056 --> 00:15.102
- Courtney, I found Dad.

00:15.145 --> 00:16.451
- You were right.

00:16.494 --> 00:18.192
I've been feverishly
trying to make up for all

00:18.235 --> 00:19.889
of my shortcomings,

00:19.932 --> 00:22.413
been wounding myself
so that you can save me.

00:22.457 --> 00:25.503
I am not the problem.
You are.

00:25.547 --> 00:29.812
- Leyla, this is a bad idea.
- So?

00:29.855 --> 00:32.293
- Let's get married tomorrow.

00:32.336 --> 00:33.685
In New York.

00:33.729 --> 00:35.078
Okay, what do you
need for a wedding?

00:35.122 --> 00:36.123
You need two people in love.

00:36.166 --> 00:37.167
You need a couple of people,

00:37.211 --> 00:38.560
a couple
of friends to witness it.

00:38.603 --> 00:39.865
Is that a yes?

00:39.909 --> 00:41.345
- Yes!
Yes!

00:41.389 --> 00:43.086
Yes!

00:44.740 --> 00:47.308
[bright music]

00:47.351 --> 00:49.658
- I didn't have to sit on my
suitcase to do up the zip,

00:49.701 --> 00:51.790
which makes me think
I've wildly under packed.

00:51.834 --> 00:54.358
- Well,
who says you need clothes?

00:54.402 --> 00:57.057
- I love it when you're cheeky.

00:57.100 --> 00:59.668
I'll be at Heathrow in an hour.

00:59.711 --> 01:01.539
This is really
happening, isn't it?

01:01.583 --> 01:03.411
- This is really happening.

01:03.454 --> 01:05.543
I just spoke
to the fine folks at

01:05.587 --> 01:09.156
the botanical garden,
and they are ready

01:09.199 --> 01:11.288
for an intimate ceremony
with our closest friends.

01:11.332 --> 01:14.726
And they even threw in some
exotic flowers for free.

01:14.770 --> 01:16.206
- And Luna?

01:16.250 --> 01:17.729
- I'm heading to Connecticut
to pick her up now,

01:17.773 --> 01:20.602
and what I'm being told
is her big girl princess dress,

01:20.645 --> 01:23.909
I'm assuming, Gwen went
for maximum cuteness here.

01:23.953 --> 01:25.694
- Of course she did.

01:25.737 --> 01:27.217
- Hey, what's
your flight number?

01:27.261 --> 01:29.741
- It's 476.

01:29.785 --> 01:31.003
Why?

01:31.047 --> 01:32.092
Are you tracking me?

01:32.135 --> 01:33.963
- You know I am.
Are you kidding me?

01:34.006 --> 01:36.226
I can't wait to see you.

01:36.270 --> 01:39.142
♪

01:39.186 --> 01:40.709
- I love you.

01:40.752 --> 01:43.190
- I love you more.

01:43.233 --> 01:44.582
- High chance
these two systems

01:44.626 --> 01:47.019
will miss each other
by about 12 hours.

01:47.063 --> 01:48.760
Alba will be ocean bound
by this afternoon.

01:48.804 --> 01:50.458
[thunder cracking]

01:50.501 --> 01:52.503
We will keep you updated,
so please stay tuned.

01:56.594 --> 01:59.423
- Well, Samira is
nestled at her sleepover,

01:59.467 --> 02:01.904
and she promises not
to call for us at 11:00.

02:01.947 --> 02:03.645
- Hmm, that's sweet.

02:03.688 --> 02:06.213
It's a total lie,
but it's sweet.

02:06.256 --> 02:09.172
[chuckling]

02:09.216 --> 02:12.567
- Um, so...

02:14.743 --> 02:16.832
Are we ever gonna
talk about the other night?

02:18.660 --> 02:20.792
- You mean about me
being the problem

02:20.836 --> 02:22.142
in our relationship?

02:22.185 --> 02:25.362
I don't quite know what to say,
to be honest.

02:25.406 --> 02:27.364
- Oh, Martin, I...

02:32.239 --> 02:35.285
You know,
the night that we met,

02:35.329 --> 02:37.592
that was the most
breathtaking night of my life.

02:37.635 --> 02:40.812
I mean, there I was, doing my
usual gay bar routine of just

02:40.856 --> 02:43.119
standing there awkwardly,
not talking to anybody,

02:43.163 --> 02:47.254
eyes down, and, uh,
this gorgeous man comes over

02:47.297 --> 02:49.430
and says, "hello", to me.

02:52.694 --> 02:54.391
But why me?

02:54.435 --> 02:57.177
[soft dramatic music]

02:57.220 --> 02:59.744
- Because you were cute.

02:59.788 --> 03:01.616
- There were lots
of cuter guys there.

03:03.270 --> 03:05.881
- Not to me, they weren't.

03:05.924 --> 03:07.187
I saw something in you.

03:07.230 --> 03:08.492
- Martin, you didn't--

03:10.886 --> 03:15.369
You didn't look across the bar
and see into my soul.

03:15.412 --> 03:16.979
You didn't.

03:17.022 --> 03:19.503
You came over because
part of you was drawn

03:19.547 --> 03:22.332
to broken birds
that need to be saved.

03:22.376 --> 03:26.380
And I'm not--I'm not
a broken bird anymore.

03:29.992 --> 03:32.124
I love you,

03:32.168 --> 03:35.737
but sometimes it just--
it feels like you have

03:35.780 --> 03:38.043
this need to be the strong one,

03:38.087 --> 03:42.831
and in order for you
to be the strong one,

03:42.874 --> 03:44.528
I need to be weak.

03:46.095 --> 03:50.055
- Okay, I hear you.

03:50.099 --> 03:52.754
- Okay, thank you.

03:52.797 --> 03:54.712
- And I can't believe
you have the gall to say

03:54.756 --> 03:58.325
that our problem
is that I am too supportive

03:58.368 --> 04:01.719
because there is nobody,
Iggy, and I mean nobody,

04:01.763 --> 04:04.418
who wishes you weren't broken
more than me.

04:04.461 --> 04:06.463
It has been
your go-to move for years,

04:06.507 --> 04:08.291
and as far as I can see,

04:08.335 --> 04:10.859
you have no interest
in changing that.

04:10.902 --> 04:17.822
♪

04:20.085 --> 04:21.913
- Somebody need a half caf,

04:21.957 --> 04:24.786
with two shakes
of cinnamon and extra foam?

04:26.091 --> 04:27.484
- You didn't have to do that.

04:27.528 --> 04:29.660
- Why not?
It's not your drink anymore?

04:29.704 --> 04:32.272
- It--it is.
It is.

04:32.315 --> 04:35.231
Um, it's perfect.

04:35.275 --> 04:37.799
Just didn't think
you remembered.

04:42.151 --> 04:45.110
[tender music]

04:45.154 --> 04:48.331
♪

04:48.375 --> 04:50.420
- What meme are we all
obsessing over now?

04:50.464 --> 04:52.335
Come on.
- Not a meme.

04:52.379 --> 04:53.858
A storm.

04:53.902 --> 04:56.296
- With the sudden
trajectory shift,

04:56.339 --> 04:58.036
Hurricane Alba is now slated

04:58.080 --> 05:01.083
to hit New York City
and the surrounding areas.

05:01.126 --> 05:04.347
Citizens in Lower Manhattan
are advised to evacuate

05:04.391 --> 05:07.872
and seek shelter above
sea level for the duration

05:07.916 --> 05:11.049
of what is now considered
a category 4 storm.

05:12.660 --> 05:14.357
- It is
heading straight for us.

05:14.401 --> 05:15.967
We can't
have a repeat of Sandy.

05:16.011 --> 05:18.143
As the new medical director,
what's your plan

05:18.187 --> 05:20.058
to save this hospital
and everyone in it?

05:20.102 --> 05:21.190
[upbeat music]

05:21.233 --> 05:23.975
- I'm open to ideas.

05:24.019 --> 05:25.542
- What do you mean
Dr. Langford can't lead

05:25.586 --> 05:27.239
the emergency response?

05:27.283 --> 05:28.545
- I mean, he's not equipped.

05:28.589 --> 05:31.418
He literally asked me
where the bathrooms were.

05:31.461 --> 05:32.767
- What about Max?

05:32.810 --> 05:34.116
- Oh, you mean the guy
getting married tomorrow,

05:34.159 --> 05:36.727
who no longer works here?
Why can't you come in?

05:36.771 --> 05:38.860
- Well, if the hurricane's
changed directions once,

05:38.903 --> 05:40.601
it'll probably
change direction again.

05:40.644 --> 05:42.080
- Yeah, and if it doesn't?

05:42.124 --> 05:43.778
- Look, I'm finally getting

05:43.821 --> 05:45.388
some answers
to some personal stuff

05:45.432 --> 05:47.129
I've been putting off
my whole life,

05:47.172 --> 05:48.870
and I can't turn back now.

05:48.913 --> 05:49.827
- Geez,
if you don't want to lead

05:49.871 --> 05:52.003
the response team, just say no.

05:52.047 --> 05:54.005
- No?
- No!

05:54.049 --> 05:57.095
- I lack the institutional
knowledge to guide

05:57.139 --> 05:58.880
the hospital
through something this big.

05:58.923 --> 06:01.186
One day I hope to,
but that's not today so...

06:01.230 --> 06:02.666
- No--no.

06:02.710 --> 06:04.842
- My department
is literally bursting

06:04.886 --> 06:06.409
with patients
I have to evacuate,

06:06.453 --> 06:08.542
and yours is not.

06:08.585 --> 06:10.674
I just mean the needs
of your department

06:10.718 --> 06:12.981
are non-critical.
- It just arrived.

06:13.024 --> 06:14.678
They're prepping
Mr. Clingman in OR-2.

06:14.722 --> 06:15.897
- Excuse me,
I've got to go put this

06:15.940 --> 06:18.552
non-critical heart
in Mr. Clingman's chest.

06:18.595 --> 06:20.858
- I barely survived
Hurricane Fuentes,

06:20.902 --> 06:23.121
and now you want to put me in
the path of a real hurricane?

06:23.165 --> 06:26.081
[rain pattering]

06:29.563 --> 06:32.522
[soft dramatic music]

06:32.566 --> 06:34.872
♪

06:34.916 --> 06:37.701
- What's wrong with you?
Your weather app broken?

06:37.745 --> 06:40.269
You usually live
for this kind of thing.

06:40.312 --> 06:43.533
- Yeah--yeah, I'm just not--
I'm not feeling it today.

06:43.577 --> 06:45.709
- Yeah, you and me both.

06:45.753 --> 06:47.145
You know,
I asked every department head

06:47.189 --> 06:49.321
in this hospital
to lead us through the storm,

06:49.365 --> 06:50.932
and every single one of them
said no.

06:53.021 --> 06:54.979
- You didn't ask me.

06:55.023 --> 06:56.938
- You really think
taking control

06:56.981 --> 06:59.244
and leading a response team
is in your wheelhouse?

06:59.288 --> 07:01.159
- In my wheelhouse?

07:01.203 --> 07:03.553
You don't think I can do it?
- I didn't say that.

07:03.597 --> 07:04.946
- Give me that binder.
Let me see this.

07:04.989 --> 07:06.382
- Iggy.

07:06.426 --> 07:08.428
- No, no, no, not another--
no, not another word.

07:08.471 --> 07:10.517
I am in charge now.
Thank you.

07:12.040 --> 07:14.956
[doorbell buzzing]
[thunder crashing]

07:19.308 --> 07:20.657
- Took you long enough!

07:20.701 --> 07:22.790
Come in!
Come in!

07:22.833 --> 07:24.052
- Uh.

07:28.012 --> 07:29.187
- Watch your head.

07:29.231 --> 07:30.624
Mr. Horace is in the back.

07:30.667 --> 07:32.930
How he thought he could get
all this storm prep done

07:32.974 --> 07:35.280
by himself
with that hurricane

07:35.324 --> 07:37.108
around the corner is beyond me.

07:37.152 --> 07:39.850
That's why I insisted that he
call to get some real help.

07:39.894 --> 07:41.765
Just didn't think that help
would be so well dressed.

07:41.809 --> 07:43.637
Mr. Horus, your friend is here.

07:47.162 --> 07:49.077
- Hello, Mr. Horace.

07:49.120 --> 07:51.296
[thunder rumbling]

07:51.340 --> 07:53.777
♪

07:53.821 --> 07:57.085
- Don't just stand there.
Grab those sandbags.

07:57.128 --> 07:58.782
Let's get to it.

08:02.960 --> 08:05.180
- Coming through.
Oh, God.

08:05.223 --> 08:07.965
Uh, hi--hi, everyone.

08:08.009 --> 08:09.489
Can I have
your attention, please?

08:09.532 --> 08:11.621
Everybody, your attention?

08:11.665 --> 08:13.841
- Hey, listen up!

08:13.884 --> 08:16.321
[fast-paced dramatic music]

08:16.365 --> 08:17.627
- Thank you.

08:17.671 --> 08:19.629
Uh, yeah, so as some of you

08:19.673 --> 08:20.978
may recall
from Hurricane Sandy,

08:21.022 --> 08:23.067
the ED will be
the first place to flood,

08:23.111 --> 08:24.982
so everything
and everyone not nailed

08:25.026 --> 08:26.897
to the floor down here
needs to be moved up or out.

08:26.941 --> 08:28.682
Capeesh?

08:28.725 --> 08:30.814
Okay, thank you.
As you were.

08:32.207 --> 08:34.644
- Very professional.
- You patronizing me?

08:34.688 --> 08:36.124
- No, never.

08:36.167 --> 08:37.778
You seem like you know
exactly what you were doing.

08:37.821 --> 08:39.649
- It's all in the binder,
I have no idea what I'm doing.

08:39.693 --> 08:42.260
- Hey, hey, we need
some help over here!

08:42.304 --> 08:43.958
- Sir, sir, we're not
set up for her right now.

08:44.001 --> 08:45.742
- Please, she can barely walk.

08:45.786 --> 08:48.440
- Dr. Bloom, I got you.
- Okay.

08:48.484 --> 08:50.225
- Ow!

08:50.268 --> 08:52.183
- Hey, what's your name?
- Her name's April.

08:52.227 --> 08:54.011
- Okay,
is the pain in your stomach?

08:54.055 --> 08:56.231
Okay, I'm just gonna
lightly press.

08:56.274 --> 08:58.276
- [painful moaning]

08:58.320 --> 09:00.496
- When was your
last menstrual cycle?

09:00.540 --> 09:03.847
♪

09:03.891 --> 09:06.110
- Do you think she's pregnant?

09:06.154 --> 09:08.939
- I'm just gonna check
your lymph nodes.

09:11.072 --> 09:13.030
Okay, well,
your symptoms are consistent

09:13.074 --> 09:14.945
with that
of an ectopic pregnancy.

09:14.989 --> 09:17.861
That's when the embryo
grows outside of the womb.

09:17.905 --> 09:20.211
Left untreated,
it can be life threatening.

09:20.255 --> 09:21.735
- Oh, my God.

09:21.778 --> 09:26.914
♪

09:26.957 --> 09:29.699
- Huxley, uh, Bay 26.

09:29.743 --> 09:32.572
Excuse me.
Dr. Shinwari?

09:35.444 --> 09:37.881
- Want me to take
the boyfriend up to charting?

09:37.925 --> 09:40.101
- That's not her boyfriend.

09:40.144 --> 09:43.583
That tattoo behind her ear,
I've seen it before.

09:43.626 --> 09:46.673
That woman's
being sex trafficked.

09:46.716 --> 09:48.631
[thunder crashing]

09:48.675 --> 09:50.764
[soft dramatic music]

09:50.807 --> 09:57.771
♪

10:16.528 --> 10:18.966
- No, no, no, no, no!
Help!

10:19.009 --> 10:20.750
[screams]

10:20.794 --> 10:23.274
♪

10:23.318 --> 10:24.667
- Okay, okay.

10:24.711 --> 10:26.451
Relocate patients
to higher floor, check.

10:26.495 --> 10:30.412
Transport all vital materials
to corresponding floors, check.

10:30.455 --> 10:33.154
Uh--
- So now what?

10:33.197 --> 10:35.417
We just wait?

10:35.460 --> 10:37.071
- I, uh--I don't know.

10:37.114 --> 10:39.247
Let me check on that.
Let's see.

10:39.290 --> 10:40.640
Oh.
Oh!

10:40.683 --> 10:41.771
[crowd gasping]

10:41.815 --> 10:43.773
- Uh.
Uh, that's fine.

10:43.817 --> 10:45.470
That's fine.
Nobody panic.

10:45.514 --> 10:48.778
Our main grid has gone down
and, um, our backup generators

10:48.822 --> 10:50.954
should kick back on
in about 5 seconds, okay?

10:50.998 --> 10:53.783
Five Mississippi,
four Mississippi,

10:53.827 --> 10:56.394
three Mississippi,
two Mississippi,

10:56.438 --> 10:58.092
and one Mississippi.

11:00.529 --> 11:05.403
One Miss-iss-ipp-i!

11:05.447 --> 11:07.231
There it is.

11:07.275 --> 11:08.537
Okay,
apparently we just needed

11:08.580 --> 11:10.408
a slightly longer state name.

11:10.452 --> 11:12.323
Okay, everyone,
make yourselves at home,

11:12.367 --> 11:14.804
and like my friends in
the meteorology community say,

11:14.848 --> 11:16.806
we will weather
this weather together.

11:16.850 --> 11:18.721
All right?

11:18.765 --> 11:20.070
[glass shattering]

11:20.114 --> 11:21.724
Whoa!

11:21.768 --> 11:23.030
- [screams]

11:26.729 --> 11:27.121
.

11:27.164 --> 11:28.513
[thunder crashing]

11:28.557 --> 11:30.472
[dramatic music]

11:30.515 --> 11:32.343
♪

11:32.387 --> 11:33.997
- Iggy!

11:34.041 --> 11:35.607
It's not safe here.

11:35.651 --> 11:37.305
We have to move somewhere else.
- Okay--okay, yeah.

11:37.348 --> 11:39.220
I think everyone is headed
to the EV overflow, right?

11:39.263 --> 11:40.351
Okay, just,
uh, give me a second.

11:40.395 --> 11:42.092
I have the right chapter
here, somewhere.

11:42.136 --> 11:44.442
- Iggy,
the binder's a lost cause.

11:44.486 --> 11:45.530
- No, no, no.

11:45.574 --> 11:46.575
No, don't--
don't--don't say that.

11:46.618 --> 11:48.272
So the only pages
that aren't wet

11:48.316 --> 11:49.621
say that we should
start putting boards

11:49.665 --> 11:51.145
on the window
24 hours in advance.

11:51.188 --> 11:52.668
All right,
if every--if everywhere

11:52.712 --> 11:54.235
with a window is dangerous,
that means we need to find

11:54.278 --> 11:55.802
somewhere without
a window, right?

11:55.845 --> 11:57.455
But this hospital is basically
made out of windows, so--

11:57.499 --> 11:59.588
- Hey, hey.
Panic's not an option.

11:59.631 --> 12:01.329
Neither is hiding.

12:01.372 --> 12:03.810
You asked to lead, so lead.

12:03.853 --> 12:05.376
♪

12:05.420 --> 12:06.682
- Okay.

12:06.726 --> 12:08.031
Yeah, thank you.

12:08.075 --> 12:10.904
Okay.
You said the magic word.

12:10.947 --> 12:12.383
- Please?
- Hide.

12:12.427 --> 12:14.255
Hey, everybody,
listen up, okay?

12:14.298 --> 12:15.647
We're gonna head
to this hospital's

12:15.691 --> 12:17.040
innermost stairwells.

12:17.084 --> 12:18.476
It is the farthest we can get
from this weather,

12:18.520 --> 12:19.956
and it happens to be
the one spot in this building

12:20.000 --> 12:21.436
that has no windows, all right?

12:21.479 --> 12:22.916
Dr. Wilder,
I need you to take the rear.

12:22.959 --> 12:23.960
Make sure
everybody makes it out.

12:24.004 --> 12:25.266
Let's go.
Everybody, come with me.

12:25.309 --> 12:26.484
All right, guys, come on.

12:26.528 --> 12:27.964
Quickly and safely.
Quickly and safely.

12:28.008 --> 12:29.792
- We have to get April
away from him.

12:29.836 --> 12:31.707
- We don't even know if she
wants to get away from him.

12:31.751 --> 12:33.274
- She's been
branded like property.

12:33.317 --> 12:35.145
I mean,
he barely lets her speak.

12:35.189 --> 12:37.321
- Okay, say you're right,
and she wants out.

12:37.365 --> 12:39.497
If he thinks you're onto him,
he'll take her and leave,

12:39.541 --> 12:41.325
and she'll
pay the price for that.

12:41.369 --> 12:42.805
- Well,
we have to do something.

12:42.849 --> 12:43.980
- I need some help!

12:44.024 --> 12:45.590
- Okay, keep an eye on them.

12:45.634 --> 12:46.983
I'm gonna be right back.

12:47.027 --> 12:48.158
- I got a traumatic hip injury.

12:48.202 --> 12:49.290
- Max, we're not set up
for triage.

12:49.333 --> 12:50.508
We're trying to evac--

12:50.552 --> 12:51.814
- I need to stabilize his hip,
all right?

12:51.858 --> 12:53.250
There could be internal damage.

12:53.294 --> 12:54.643
I'll be quick, but there's
no moving him until I do.

12:54.686 --> 12:56.079
- Dr. Bloom, the patient's
O2 stat is dropping.

12:56.123 --> 12:57.341
- Go, I got this.

12:57.385 --> 12:58.865
- Okay.
- Thank you.

12:58.908 --> 13:00.649
- What's going on?

13:00.692 --> 13:03.217
♪

13:09.353 --> 13:10.746
- You just
gonna leave it like that?

13:13.793 --> 13:15.707
- Like what?

13:15.751 --> 13:19.146
- You gotta pack those bags
tight against that wall.

13:19.189 --> 13:21.191
Shoot, you better
just let me do this.

13:21.235 --> 13:22.758
- No, I--I got it.

13:25.805 --> 13:27.197
- Never thought
a man in those brogues

13:27.241 --> 13:29.373
would know how to do that.

13:29.417 --> 13:31.506
- I had to teach myself.

13:36.946 --> 13:41.211
This wall ever leak before?
- Yeah, like a sieve.

13:42.996 --> 13:45.781
Owner call it
"self-remodeling the building".

13:47.696 --> 13:51.221
Got these--got these
pipes going nowhere.

13:51.265 --> 13:53.702
Beams holding up nothing.

13:53.745 --> 13:55.486
Threw up some paneling
and some paint,

13:55.530 --> 13:57.097
and suddenly the empty basement

13:57.140 --> 14:00.361
with the flooding problem
was an apartment.

14:00.404 --> 14:04.104
Miss Kate better than me,
putting up with this.

14:06.106 --> 14:08.151
- Well, it's a good thing
I came back, huh?

14:09.500 --> 14:13.243
- Oh, is it now?
'Cause I don't need no favors.

14:13.287 --> 14:16.116
I'm getting
by just fine by myself.

14:18.814 --> 14:21.382
- At least you had
a choice in the matter.

14:22.339 --> 14:24.820
- Looks like you two
have things under control.

14:24.864 --> 14:27.649
Oh, my photo albums.
It's always something.

14:27.692 --> 14:29.433
[creaking]

14:29.477 --> 14:30.434
[cracking]
- Look out!

14:30.478 --> 14:32.219
[crashing]
- Ah!

14:32.262 --> 14:35.222
[dramatic music]

14:35.265 --> 14:36.571
♪

14:36.614 --> 14:38.355
[strained breathing, moaning]

14:38.399 --> 14:40.967
- You still with me, Fareed?
- Yeah.

14:41.010 --> 14:43.317
- This is gonna make
you feel a little better, okay?

14:44.971 --> 14:46.146
Just a little pinch, okay?

14:46.189 --> 14:47.625
- My wife is gonna
kill me, Dr. Goodwin.

14:47.669 --> 14:50.541
You know how long we saved
to buy that cart?

14:50.585 --> 14:54.110
- The cart can be replaced,
but your life cannot,

14:54.154 --> 14:55.851
and, Fareed, call me Max.

14:55.895 --> 14:57.853
- Okay, Max.

15:02.640 --> 15:05.774
- I think it's working.
- Good.

15:05.817 --> 15:07.254
The sooner that pain goes down,
the sooner

15:07.297 --> 15:08.733
we can examine your hip.

15:08.777 --> 15:10.997
Now let's just give that
a minute to work...

15:11.040 --> 15:13.303
and try to relax,
all right?

15:13.347 --> 15:16.089
[soft dramatic music]

15:16.132 --> 15:22.878
♪

15:24.314 --> 15:26.360
[sighs]

15:26.403 --> 15:33.410
♪

15:33.454 --> 15:35.499
- Max?
- Yeah?

15:39.373 --> 15:42.158
- I--think I soiled myself.

15:42.202 --> 15:43.507
- It happens.

15:43.551 --> 15:46.510
We'll get you cleaned up,
and--and--and, um...

15:48.643 --> 15:50.950
Fareed, have you ever had
kidney problems in the past?

15:50.993 --> 15:53.517
- I donated one to my daughter,
but the other

15:53.561 --> 15:55.563
has been working fine, why?

15:55.606 --> 15:56.999
- I think your kidney
is failing, and I think

15:57.043 --> 15:59.393
we need to get you upstairs
to a dialysis machine

15:59.436 --> 16:01.308
right now, or--
we need to go now.

16:03.614 --> 16:05.051
- Watch your step, please.
Okay.

16:05.094 --> 16:07.227
Come on everybody,
we should be safe in here.

16:07.270 --> 16:09.403
All right?

16:09.446 --> 16:11.187
Okay, go on.

16:11.231 --> 16:13.755
Yeah, go on.
Okay.

16:13.798 --> 16:15.452
Okay, great, great.
Thank you, everybody.

16:15.496 --> 16:18.238
Thank you for your cooperation.

16:18.281 --> 16:19.848
Uh...

16:22.242 --> 16:24.418
- You should say something.
- Yeah.

16:24.461 --> 16:25.897
- They seem really scared.
- Yeah, yeah, okay.

16:25.941 --> 16:28.030
Okay, so I know that that was
very unnerving for a lot

16:28.074 --> 16:31.120
of you, but I promise you,
we are--we are protected here.

16:31.164 --> 16:32.817
We are very safe
from the storm.

16:32.861 --> 16:34.341
And the good news is
we only have to huddle

16:34.384 --> 16:36.212
in here for
the next four or five hours.

16:36.256 --> 16:37.561
- Four or five hours?

16:37.605 --> 16:39.607
- Yeah, yes,
it's for all of our safety.

16:39.650 --> 16:41.217
- I can't breathe in here.

16:41.261 --> 16:42.653
- Being enclosed
in a tight space

16:42.697 --> 16:44.220
can trigger physical reactions.

16:44.264 --> 16:46.135
That's perfectly normal,
okay, everybody?

16:46.179 --> 16:48.355
But I promise you,
you truly have nothing to fear.

16:48.398 --> 16:49.834
- I can't breathe either.

16:49.878 --> 16:50.879
- Okay, guys,

16:50.922 --> 16:52.359
simple breathing exercise,
okay?

16:52.402 --> 16:53.882
Maybe everyone can
just close their eyes

16:53.925 --> 16:56.145
and listen to the sound
of my voice, okay?

16:56.189 --> 16:58.147
And take
a couple of deep breaths...

16:58.191 --> 16:59.757
[inhales]

16:59.801 --> 17:01.629
Getting more relaxed
with each breath.

17:01.672 --> 17:03.283
Oh, oh!
- [retches]

17:03.326 --> 17:05.502
- Gladys, you all right?
- I'm sorry.

17:05.546 --> 17:08.375
- [gasps]
- Oh, oh!

17:08.418 --> 17:09.941
- What's happening to us?

17:09.985 --> 17:11.508
- I, uh--I--I don't know.

17:11.552 --> 17:13.293
♪

17:13.336 --> 17:16.035
I can't breathe either.

17:16.078 --> 17:18.820
[labored breaths]

17:23.085 --> 17:23.259
.

17:23.303 --> 17:26.915
- I can't breathe.
I can't breathe!

17:26.958 --> 17:28.656
- Okay, all right,
I gotcha, I gotcha.

17:28.699 --> 17:30.397
Let's just--

17:30.440 --> 17:32.921
Hey, I think--I think
her airway--airway's blocked.

17:32.964 --> 17:34.575
- No, no.
- No?

17:34.618 --> 17:35.837
Um...

17:35.880 --> 17:37.317
Cardiac arrest?

17:37.360 --> 17:39.580
- No.
- No?

17:39.623 --> 17:41.364
What?

17:41.408 --> 17:43.758
[air hissing]

17:43.801 --> 17:45.934
What is it?
Okay, breathe, breathe.

17:45.977 --> 17:48.067
What have you got?
What have you got?

17:49.285 --> 17:51.940
Carbon monoxide.
Carbon monoxide!

17:51.983 --> 17:55.030
Okay, carbon--okay.

17:55.074 --> 17:57.119
Okay, hey, we gotta move.

17:57.163 --> 17:59.687
We gotta move, everyone.
Come on.

17:59.730 --> 18:03.778
Nice and slow, take it easy.
Nice and slow, everybody.

18:03.821 --> 18:05.562
- I don't--
I don't want to die.

18:05.606 --> 18:08.261
- We got you, Mrs. K.
- Put your back into it!

18:08.304 --> 18:11.438
- We're getting it.
[straining]

18:11.481 --> 18:12.656
- [coughs]

18:12.700 --> 18:13.657
- All right, okay.
- The beam.

18:13.701 --> 18:15.050
- The beam.
The beam.

18:15.094 --> 18:16.878
Here.
- Help me.

18:16.921 --> 18:19.707
Come on.
Come on.

18:19.750 --> 18:22.710
[straining]

18:22.753 --> 18:24.842
- [gasps]

18:24.886 --> 18:27.062
[soft dramatic music]

18:27.106 --> 18:29.630
- She can't breathe.
She's got two minutes tops.

18:29.673 --> 18:31.153
Wait!

18:31.197 --> 18:32.937
- [whimpering]
- I'm not leaving you, okay?

18:32.981 --> 18:34.896
I'm here with you.
I got you, all right?

18:34.939 --> 18:38.160
- I'm gonna lever that pipe up,
then you can pull her out.

18:38.204 --> 18:40.075
- All right.
Come on, come on.

18:40.119 --> 18:43.600
- [straining]
Come on!

18:43.644 --> 18:44.819
Come on...

18:44.862 --> 18:46.299
We've got it clear.
Get her out!

18:48.039 --> 18:49.302
[pipe thuds]

18:52.957 --> 18:55.960
- Okay, help me get her
to the table.

18:56.004 --> 18:58.180
Nice and easy, nice and easy.

18:58.224 --> 19:01.227
Okay, yep, take her back
just like that, all right.

19:01.270 --> 19:04.926
- I thought moving that pipe
was gonna fix her.

19:09.496 --> 19:11.411
- Is that her bone?

19:12.107 --> 19:13.848
- Gonna need some rags,
your needle nose pliers,

19:13.891 --> 19:15.110
and some plastic wrap.

19:15.154 --> 19:16.459
- What are you
gonna do with that?

19:17.634 --> 19:19.201
- I'm gonna save her life.

19:19.245 --> 19:21.290
- Yeah,
just down the hall, guys.

19:21.334 --> 19:23.031
Okay, all right.

19:23.074 --> 19:24.250
Nice and slow.

19:24.293 --> 19:26.121
- Oh, hey, Iggy.
- Oh, my God.

19:26.165 --> 19:28.863
Oh, Max, like mana from heaven,
oh, my God.

19:28.906 --> 19:29.994
Are you here to take over?
- What?

19:30.038 --> 19:31.518
No, I heard you're in charge.

19:31.561 --> 19:34.956
- I got people shredded
by flying glass in the ICU,

19:34.999 --> 19:36.523
poisoned by gas
in the stairwell,

19:36.566 --> 19:38.655
and now my EPM is destroyed,
and I have no idea

19:38.699 --> 19:39.874
what I'm gonna do next, Max.

19:39.917 --> 19:41.005
These people
are gonna see through me.

19:41.049 --> 19:42.746
- There's a gas leak
in the stairwell?

19:42.790 --> 19:43.965
- That's your takeaway?

19:44.008 --> 19:45.184
- I have a patient
who needs dialysis.

19:45.227 --> 19:46.446
The elevator's down.

19:46.489 --> 19:47.664
Now you're telling me
the stairs are, too?

19:47.708 --> 19:49.057
- Iggy.
- Yeah?

19:49.100 --> 19:50.232
- Go, go, go.
You're doing everything right.

19:50.276 --> 19:52.408
it's just a few bad breaks.

19:52.452 --> 19:54.105
- Okay.

19:56.064 --> 19:57.674
- So how do we get up
to the sixth floor?

20:00.764 --> 20:03.637
[wind howling]

20:04.986 --> 20:08.250
Max, can't we wait
for the storm to pass?

20:08.294 --> 20:10.252
- You won't make it if we do.

20:10.296 --> 20:13.037
It's okay.
Slow and steady, all right?

20:14.169 --> 20:18.129
[rain splashing]

20:18.173 --> 20:20.567
[thunder cracks]

20:20.610 --> 20:22.003
- Oh.

20:34.320 --> 20:36.278
- Okay, April,
let's get you set up.

20:36.322 --> 20:37.801
- Where--
where are you taking her?

20:37.845 --> 20:40.326
- We just need a urine sample.
It'll just take a minute.

20:41.152 --> 20:42.545
- There's just
so many people around.

20:42.589 --> 20:44.939
I don't
want us to get separated.

20:44.982 --> 20:46.680
- Understood.

20:46.723 --> 20:49.552
He can wait outside
the door for you, April.

20:49.596 --> 20:53.295
♪

20:53.339 --> 20:54.818
Okay.

20:54.862 --> 21:01.129
♪

21:01.172 --> 21:04.350
Okay, if you just give it back
to me when you're done, okay?

21:04.393 --> 21:05.786
Okay.

21:05.829 --> 21:12.706
♪

21:26.676 --> 21:29.462
- How much longer is
this going to take?

21:32.378 --> 21:34.118
- We're gonna get right on it.

21:34.162 --> 21:41.169
♪

21:41.212 --> 21:43.214
- Okay, everybody follow me.

21:43.258 --> 21:45.478
Keep following me.
We're almost there.

21:45.521 --> 21:47.088
- Wait, dead end?

21:47.131 --> 21:48.350
- No, listen, listen,
it's not a problem.

21:48.394 --> 21:50.047
We just have to--
we've got to move

21:50.091 --> 21:52.223
some of this debris
out of the way.

21:52.267 --> 21:54.400
Hey, everybody,
can you hear my voice?

21:54.443 --> 21:56.010
There's more than enough room
for everyone to park

21:56.053 --> 21:57.141
in here while we get this done.

21:57.185 --> 21:58.491
Okay?
Piece of cake.

21:58.534 --> 22:00.493
- Do we have any blankets?
It's freezing.

22:00.536 --> 22:02.364
- No, no, guys,
we're not staying here, okay?

22:02.408 --> 22:04.366
We just need to get through
this ward, and once we do,

22:04.410 --> 22:05.585
we're right next
to the ED overflow,

22:05.628 --> 22:07.108
and there Dr. Bloom
and her entire team

22:07.151 --> 22:08.805
is gonna be able
to treat everyone.

22:08.849 --> 22:10.851
All right, that's good news,
so just come on.

22:10.894 --> 22:13.027
I need you to stay with me
and help me push through.

22:13.070 --> 22:16.204
[straining]

22:19.294 --> 22:21.165
That's not happening.

22:21.209 --> 22:23.690
Uh, okay, um...

22:23.733 --> 22:25.605
All right, new plan,
new plan everybody.

22:25.648 --> 22:27.041
My bad, follow me.

22:27.084 --> 22:28.956
Come on, it's okay.

22:28.999 --> 22:31.219
[crashing and thudding]

22:31.262 --> 22:33.917
- Whoa!
- [screams]

22:33.961 --> 22:36.050
[electricity crackling]

22:36.093 --> 22:38.095
♪

22:44.928 --> 22:45.146
.

22:45.189 --> 22:47.017
- Yeah, yeah sheets.

22:47.061 --> 22:48.497
- All right,
we need to mop this up now.

22:48.541 --> 22:49.933
- Lay them flat so we
can mop up as much as possible.

22:49.977 --> 22:51.282
Come on, everybody,
lay 'em down.

22:51.326 --> 22:52.632
- Yeah,
but it's pouring out there.

22:52.675 --> 22:53.807
We don't have enough
sheets to stop it.

22:53.850 --> 22:55.025
- Can we call somebody?
- No, no, no.

22:55.069 --> 22:56.592
Internet, Wi-Fi, phones,
they're all down.

22:56.636 --> 22:58.420
No one even knows
that we're in here.

22:58.464 --> 23:00.248
Yeah, spread them out.

23:00.291 --> 23:04.295
- What do we do?
- Uh, we, uh--we, uh...

23:05.906 --> 23:07.821
We--we shut off
the backup generators.

23:07.864 --> 23:09.736
- And kill any patients
on ventilators too?

23:09.779 --> 23:11.128
- No, they'll all be
on portable generators by now.

23:11.172 --> 23:12.434
Everybody will.
This is it.

23:12.478 --> 23:13.435
This is the plan.

23:13.479 --> 23:14.958
- I'm pretty sure the binder

23:15.002 --> 23:16.220
wouldn't approve of turning off
the backup generators.

23:16.264 --> 23:17.483
- There's no binder.
There's no binder.

23:17.526 --> 23:18.788
It's just us.

23:18.832 --> 23:21.835
[electricity crackling]

23:21.878 --> 23:24.751
[soft dramatic music]

23:24.794 --> 23:29.712
♪

23:29.756 --> 23:32.933
- Iggy, if you even graze

23:32.976 --> 23:35.414
that wire, you'll die.

23:35.457 --> 23:42.377
♪

23:52.692 --> 23:54.824
- You in some good hands
right now.

23:54.868 --> 23:57.131
The best, some might say.

23:57.174 --> 24:00.047
Yeah, that young man over there
who's working on you,

24:00.090 --> 24:03.485
he a big time heart surgeon,
Yale educated,

24:03.529 --> 24:05.487
top of his class,
you know that?

24:05.531 --> 24:07.620
[chuckles]

24:10.840 --> 24:12.233
- What are you
giving me those for?

24:12.276 --> 24:14.278
- Look, you're gonna take
the exposed end

24:14.322 --> 24:16.933
of that bone
and push it back in.

24:16.977 --> 24:19.806
Now, look,
the ribcage is curved,

24:19.849 --> 24:21.938
so it should
just glide back in.

24:21.982 --> 24:23.940
Here you go.
- No, I'm not a doctor.

24:23.984 --> 24:26.421
- Well, look, I can't do this
with my hands alone.

24:26.465 --> 24:28.292
All right?

24:28.336 --> 24:30.904
Look, you're working
on a car engine.

24:35.125 --> 24:36.779
- Okay.

24:36.823 --> 24:38.433
- All right.

24:40.783 --> 24:44.439
- [whimpers in pain]
- Okay, all right.

24:44.483 --> 24:45.614
- Just push it on down.

24:45.658 --> 24:46.789
Yeah,
just a little bit further.

24:46.833 --> 24:48.443
Careful, hold on, hold on.

24:48.487 --> 24:50.053
There you go.
Okay, hold it right there.

24:50.097 --> 24:52.186
Don't move, don't move.
Just--okay, just relax.

24:56.059 --> 24:58.801
Now that that's in place,
she should...

24:58.845 --> 25:00.760
[wheezing for breath]

25:00.803 --> 25:02.152
- What's happening?

25:02.196 --> 25:05.025
- There's tension
in her thorax.

25:05.068 --> 25:06.417
I just need a pen.
I need a pen.

25:06.461 --> 25:07.941
Get me that pen, that pen.

25:07.984 --> 25:10.378
Hurry, hurry, hurry, hurry,
hurry, hurry, hurry, okay.

25:17.603 --> 25:20.519
- [inhales deeply]

25:20.562 --> 25:22.433
[exhales deeply]

25:22.477 --> 25:24.174
♪

25:24.218 --> 25:25.785
- There we go.

25:28.352 --> 25:29.876
- You're okay.

25:31.442 --> 25:35.011
- April, we got your labs back,
and they are positive.

25:35.055 --> 25:37.536
You are definitely pregnant.

25:37.579 --> 25:39.668
- Oh, okay.

25:39.712 --> 25:41.801
- Hey, hey,
it's all good, babe.

25:42.845 --> 25:44.412
- Since this is ectopic,

25:44.455 --> 25:47.023
the best way to resolve
is surgery.

25:47.067 --> 25:50.287
- Okay.
- What kind of surgery?

25:50.331 --> 25:53.464
- A laparotomy is the best--
- Why are you lying to us?

25:53.508 --> 25:55.466
- I'm not.

25:55.510 --> 25:56.990
- A nurse just told me
this could all be

25:57.033 --> 25:58.295
fixed with some pills.

25:59.645 --> 26:01.821
- Pills can be used
with some ectopic pregnancies.

26:01.864 --> 26:03.997
- But why not this one?

26:04.040 --> 26:06.390
- Based on the gestational age
of the embryo and where--

26:06.434 --> 26:08.958
- Yeah, we'll take our chances
with the pills.

26:09.002 --> 26:10.569
It's our choice, right?

26:10.612 --> 26:11.874
- Well, it's April's choice.

26:13.963 --> 26:15.965
Look, look,
I know you want to get out

26:16.009 --> 26:17.488
of here, but this is
a super safe procedure--

26:17.532 --> 26:19.578
- Yeah, we're out of here.

26:19.621 --> 26:21.754
♪

26:21.797 --> 26:24.713
[electricity crackling]

26:24.757 --> 26:31.938
♪

26:35.419 --> 26:37.944
- [coughs]
I don't feel so good.

26:37.987 --> 26:39.772
- Just hang on, okay?

26:39.815 --> 26:41.687
Here we are.
Here we are.

26:41.730 --> 26:43.210
Okay.

26:53.786 --> 26:55.309
[device beeps]

26:57.311 --> 26:58.268
Okay.

26:59.487 --> 27:00.662
We're gonna get
your kidney functioning

27:00.706 --> 27:02.011
in no time, all right?

27:02.055 --> 27:04.100
Just let this machine work.

27:29.125 --> 27:32.520
- Max, what's happening?
- We just lost power.

27:35.349 --> 27:37.786
- He did it.
Iggy did it.

27:37.830 --> 27:39.788
- Quickly, everyone, let's go!

27:39.832 --> 27:42.791
[indistinct chatter]

27:42.835 --> 27:44.663
- Hey!
Excuse me!

27:44.706 --> 27:46.142
Wait!

27:49.058 --> 27:50.930
Take these.

27:50.973 --> 27:53.236
They'll terminate
the ectopic pregnancy.

27:53.280 --> 27:56.109
You'll need to watch her
closely for the next 24 hours.

27:56.152 --> 27:58.154
She could
still suffer from a rupture.

27:58.198 --> 28:00.635
If she starts running
a high fever or menstruating

28:00.679 --> 28:04.030
more than normal, just--
just bring her straight back.

28:05.074 --> 28:06.946
- I'll watch her.

28:08.730 --> 28:10.471
See, baby?

28:10.514 --> 28:12.038
Everything's fine.

28:14.780 --> 28:18.435
April?
April!

28:18.479 --> 28:25.399
♪

28:34.060 --> 28:35.322
- Okay,
first thing I'm gonna do

28:35.365 --> 28:36.540
is get you a social worker.

28:36.584 --> 28:37.977
We're gonna get you
somewhere safe.

28:39.239 --> 28:41.545
Hey, hey, you're okay.

28:41.589 --> 28:43.591
- [sobbing]
- Hey, you're okay.

28:45.593 --> 28:47.073
Oh, honey, you're okay.

28:47.116 --> 28:50.250
- [sobbing]

28:58.737 --> 29:00.521
- I can try a manual flush.

29:04.177 --> 29:06.440
Without the supplies...

29:07.528 --> 29:09.095
- There's nothing left to do,
is there?

29:09.138 --> 29:15.057
♪

29:15.101 --> 29:17.059
- Maybe call your wife.

29:27.069 --> 29:28.157
- There's no signal.

29:28.201 --> 29:35.338
♪

29:38.124 --> 29:40.430
Maybe you can tell her that

29:40.474 --> 29:42.650
when my life was
at its darkest..

29:45.522 --> 29:49.135
She was my...

29:50.397 --> 29:51.964
Light.

29:52.007 --> 29:55.141
[device beeping]

29:56.577 --> 29:58.884
- It's working.
- I've got a signal.

29:58.927 --> 30:00.668
I should call my wife.

30:02.801 --> 30:04.672
- I should call my wife too.

30:08.415 --> 30:10.678
- [speaking native language]

30:16.075 --> 30:19.556
♪

30:24.561 --> 30:24.779
.

30:24.823 --> 30:27.608
[soft dramatic music]

30:27.651 --> 30:29.088
- I'll come in
and check on you as soon

30:29.131 --> 30:31.960
as I can, Mrs. Carnegie.
- Thank you, Doctor Reynolds.

30:32.004 --> 30:35.442
- Well, there's a story, huh?
Hey, yo!

30:35.485 --> 30:37.574
Hey!

30:39.925 --> 30:42.101
- What you want?

30:42.144 --> 30:43.842
- I...

30:48.411 --> 30:50.065
I need answers.

30:53.764 --> 30:55.636
- I don't have any.

31:07.822 --> 31:08.910
Hey!

31:10.956 --> 31:14.481
Think I jacked up
my shoulder moving that beam.

31:15.961 --> 31:18.485
You know any
good shoulder doctors?

31:22.532 --> 31:24.056
- Yeah, I know a few.

31:27.146 --> 31:31.498
- Will you call me
with that number?

31:32.716 --> 31:34.675
- Yeah, I'll give you a call.

31:34.718 --> 31:41.856
♪

31:50.647 --> 31:52.954
- The social worker's
the name is Shondra.

31:52.998 --> 31:56.958
She's helped dozens of women
in the same position as you.

31:57.002 --> 32:00.570
She's gotten them help,
and she's gotten them safe.

32:00.614 --> 32:01.832
- I have a friend.

32:01.876 --> 32:03.182
I think she'll want
to come too.

32:03.225 --> 32:04.618
- You can't contact her.

32:04.661 --> 32:06.663
No one can know where you are.

32:06.707 --> 32:08.709
- But I'm not the only one.

32:08.752 --> 32:10.189
- Okay, you can talk
to the police,

32:10.232 --> 32:12.495
but you cannot have contact
with anyone

32:12.539 --> 32:14.845
you knew before
for any reason.

32:14.889 --> 32:17.196
This won't work otherwise.
Do you understand?

32:21.156 --> 32:24.333
Picking up that red pen
was the bravest thing

32:24.377 --> 32:25.291
you could have done.

32:27.032 --> 32:29.121
You took back your future...

32:31.732 --> 32:34.126
But freedom comes at a cost.

32:34.169 --> 32:41.002
♪

32:41.046 --> 32:43.570
- I never thought I'd get out.

32:45.224 --> 32:50.055
I never let myself think it
until you gave me the chance.

32:52.057 --> 32:56.017
Jackson hurt me,
made me do things that...

32:59.064 --> 33:01.196
But at least
I knew what was coming.

33:03.416 --> 33:07.115
Now, not knowing
what's next seems even scarier.

33:10.075 --> 33:12.120
But I know I've got to do it.

33:15.167 --> 33:17.691
[sobs softly]

33:19.475 --> 33:21.521
- [Whispers]
You're not alone.

33:21.564 --> 33:28.180
♪

33:28.223 --> 33:32.314
- Okay, so the ICU
is still a disaster.

33:32.358 --> 33:34.142
Gladys, maybe you can
coordinate with maintenance,

33:34.186 --> 33:35.578
see if you
can get it back online,

33:35.622 --> 33:38.059
and I'll do an inventory
of all key usable equipment.

33:38.103 --> 33:41.541
Yeah.
- Where will I be?

33:41.584 --> 33:43.673
- Building a temp ICU
with whatever I can secure.

33:43.717 --> 33:45.806
Pick a location.
I don't care where.

33:45.849 --> 33:47.590
Just make it happen,
and we'll keep the patients

33:47.634 --> 33:49.592
in Pan de Villa
'til it's up.

33:49.636 --> 33:51.377
- Okay.
- Okay.

33:52.943 --> 33:56.338
- Who needs a binder?
- [chuckles]

33:58.514 --> 34:01.082
- Oh, thank God.
- Hey, I'm okay.

34:01.126 --> 34:04.085
- Oh, how are you?
How are the kids?

34:04.129 --> 34:05.434
- They're good.
We're all good.

34:05.478 --> 34:06.653
- Good.

34:08.133 --> 34:11.049
- Did you stay in your office?
- [chuckles]

34:11.092 --> 34:14.661
Uh, no, I did
quite the opposite actually.

34:14.704 --> 34:18.317
- Didn't you get my message
to hunker down, to stay put?

34:18.360 --> 34:22.103
- Martin, I--I led the entire
hospital response team.

34:22.147 --> 34:25.672
I was in charge
of New Amsterdam.

34:25.715 --> 34:27.065
[chuckles]

34:27.108 --> 34:29.197
- Why--
why were you in charge?

34:31.373 --> 34:33.158
- Because I asked to be.

34:35.334 --> 34:38.076
- Why would you risk it?
Why would you do that?

34:41.470 --> 34:42.732
- [exhales sharply]

34:44.691 --> 34:47.041
Because I had
something to prove.

34:49.043 --> 34:51.306
You know, the only reason
I didn't think I could do it,

34:51.350 --> 34:55.441
the only thing holding me back,
was this voice in my head.

34:57.704 --> 35:00.968
And, Martin, the voice is you.

35:01.011 --> 35:08.062
♪

35:14.895 --> 35:16.418
- Well,
if that's really true, then...

35:18.899 --> 35:20.683
What are we doing?

35:20.727 --> 35:24.383
♪

35:24.426 --> 35:25.993
- I don't know.

35:28.865 --> 35:30.345
I don't know.

35:32.260 --> 35:35.394
I do know that...

35:35.437 --> 35:39.049
I can't be who I am,

35:39.093 --> 35:43.141
I can't be who I want to be

35:43.184 --> 35:44.968
with you.

35:45.012 --> 35:52.150
♪

35:59.287 --> 36:01.942
- Okay, um...

36:06.686 --> 36:08.470
Then you should move out.

36:08.514 --> 36:15.434
♪

36:28.969 --> 36:31.014
- So how's April?

36:31.058 --> 36:33.495
- She's with
a social worker now.

36:33.539 --> 36:36.019
- We make a good team,
Doctor Bloom.

36:37.282 --> 36:39.240
- I concur, Doctor Shinwari.

36:40.459 --> 36:43.940
- So...

36:43.984 --> 36:46.204
let's go
do something about it.

36:52.427 --> 36:56.910
- Earlier,
when I brought you a coffee,

36:56.953 --> 36:59.129
I saw a look on your face.

37:01.044 --> 37:03.221
Flash of worry.

37:03.264 --> 37:06.267
- No, I was appreciating it.

37:06.311 --> 37:08.443
- You were wondering
whether you had to pay me back.

37:11.881 --> 37:17.409
We started
with this money thing,

37:17.452 --> 37:19.324
and it keeps coming back.

37:22.109 --> 37:26.200
It's in everything we do,
and it's not going away.

37:28.115 --> 37:32.293
- Lauren, let's just go home,
get some sleep.

37:32.337 --> 37:36.645
- You need money,
and you need my apartment,

37:36.689 --> 37:38.560
and you need your immigration
to go through...

37:40.736 --> 37:42.956
And you need all those things
more than you need me.

37:42.999 --> 37:45.654
- No, don't say that.

37:45.698 --> 37:47.221
- What happens when we fight?

37:49.092 --> 37:51.312
You can't win
because I have all the power.

37:51.356 --> 37:53.140
What if you want
to break up with me?

37:54.794 --> 37:56.230
You can't leave.

37:56.274 --> 37:59.581
The money, it just--
just taints everything.

38:02.541 --> 38:05.108
Even me getting you
a cup of coffee.

38:08.547 --> 38:10.288
So you're gonna
take my apartment.

38:10.331 --> 38:12.812
- What?
No, no!

38:12.855 --> 38:16.424
- Yes, just until
you get your visa.

38:17.904 --> 38:20.080
And I am not gonna be there
with you.

38:22.082 --> 38:24.171
I can't be there with you.

38:30.090 --> 38:32.092
- Where will you go?

38:34.921 --> 38:36.705
- Someplace safe.

38:36.749 --> 38:39.708
[tender music]

38:39.752 --> 38:45.975
♪

38:46.019 --> 38:47.281
- Yes, well,
can you please just

38:47.325 --> 38:49.152
check the name Helen Sharpe?

38:49.196 --> 38:50.937
No, no,
I understand confidentiality,

38:50.980 --> 38:53.156
but she's my fiancée,
and she's...

38:53.200 --> 38:55.158
No, no, I don't want
to go on a brief hold.

38:55.202 --> 38:57.378
Can you just tell me
what happened to her flight?

38:57.422 --> 38:58.945
I--

39:00.816 --> 39:02.514
[phone chimes]

39:02.557 --> 39:05.255
- Oh, there you are.

39:05.299 --> 39:08.084
[phone beeps and clicks]

39:08.128 --> 39:11.087
["I'm Gonna Be [500 Miles]"]

39:11.131 --> 39:14.134
[soft tender music]

39:14.177 --> 39:16.571
- ♪ When I wake up

39:16.615 --> 39:18.791
♪ Well, I know I'm gonna be

39:18.834 --> 39:23.970
♪ I'm gonna be the man
who wakes up next to you ♪

39:24.013 --> 39:27.103
♪ And when I go out

39:27.147 --> 39:28.931
♪ Yeah, I know I'm gonna be

39:28.975 --> 39:34.415
♪ I'm gonna be the man
who goes along with you ♪

39:34.459 --> 39:36.069
♪ And when I come home

39:36.112 --> 39:38.027
- Hey, so...

39:38.071 --> 39:39.551
I know it's last minute,
but I was wondering if I

39:39.594 --> 39:41.074
could change from
the fish option

39:41.117 --> 39:43.642
to the meat option.
- Yeah, right.

39:43.685 --> 39:44.643
Just as soon as I figure out

39:44.686 --> 39:46.035
where we can even
have a ceremony.

39:46.079 --> 39:47.733
- Oh, I'm assuming
the Botanical Gardens is out.

39:47.776 --> 39:49.212
- Unless you have scuba gear.

39:49.256 --> 39:51.084
It's fine, we'll regroup.
We'll figure something out.

39:51.127 --> 39:52.564
- Hey, hold on.

39:52.607 --> 39:56.437
Actually, no need to stop
the love train over a venue.

39:56.481 --> 39:58.787
- Well, except for the fact
that we don't have one.

39:58.831 --> 40:01.442
- Actually, you do.
It's a perfect place.

40:01.486 --> 40:04.445
- ♪ And I would walk
500 more ♪

40:04.489 --> 40:07.187
♪ Just to be the man

40:07.230 --> 40:10.495
♪ Who walked
a thousand miles ♪

40:10.538 --> 40:14.324
♪ To fall down
at your door ♪

40:14.368 --> 40:16.675
♪ When I'm working

40:16.718 --> 40:19.329
- Leave a message
after the chime.

40:19.373 --> 40:22.115
- Okay, so I hope
that your dress

40:22.158 --> 40:24.160
isn't too wrinkled,
because I think

40:24.204 --> 40:28.034
we're getting married right now
on the roof at New Amsterdam.

40:28.077 --> 40:30.079
Our friends have turned
this place

40:30.123 --> 40:32.821
into magic, which is fitting

40:32.865 --> 40:34.910
because this place
has always been magic for us.

40:34.954 --> 40:37.652
It's where we work,
and it's where you and I

40:37.696 --> 40:41.351
became friends, and it's
where we fell in love,

40:41.395 --> 40:43.049
and it just makes sense
that this would be

40:43.092 --> 40:45.225
the place
that we finally start...

40:47.619 --> 40:50.143
Forever.

40:50.186 --> 40:52.493
- ♪ I'm gonna be the man
who's growing old with you ♪

40:55.148 --> 40:59.674
♪ But I would walk 500 miles

40:59.718 --> 41:02.982
♪ And I would walk 500 more

41:03.025 --> 41:04.810
[phone ringing]

41:04.853 --> 41:07.508
- ♪ Just to be the man
who walked ♪

41:07.552 --> 41:09.031
- Helen?

41:09.075 --> 41:14.646
- ♪ A thousand miles
to fall down at your door ♪

41:14.689 --> 41:18.388
♪ But I would walk 500 miles

41:18.432 --> 41:19.999
♪ And I would walk 500 more

41:20.042 --> 41:22.871
- Max, I can't.

41:22.915 --> 41:25.918
I just can't.

41:25.961 --> 41:28.486
I'm so sorry, Max.

41:28.529 --> 41:30.488
- ♪ A thousand miles
- I'm so sorry.

41:30.531 --> 41:32.359
- ♪ To fall down
at your door ♪

41:32.402 --> 41:35.318
- [sobbing softly]

41:35.362 --> 41:42.500
♪

41:53.467 --> 41:55.861
- ♪ When I wake up
- What happened?

41:55.904 --> 41:57.906
- ♪ Well,
I hope I'm gonna be ♪

41:57.950 --> 41:59.560
♪ I'm gonna be the man

41:59.604 --> 42:03.042
- She's not coming.
- ♪ Who's wakin' up to you

42:03.085 --> 42:07.046
♪ And when I'm dreaming,
well, I know I'm gonna dream ♪

42:07.089 --> 42:11.659
♪ I'm gonna dream about
the time I had with you ♪
